# Rust Modules & Crate Organisation

A well-organised crate is self-documenting. Visibility rules enforce the contract.

## Module layout

- Use `src/lib.rs` for library crates, `src/main.rs` for binaries, `src/bin/<name>.rs` for multiple binaries
- Split large modules into files: `mod foo;` in `lib.rs` picks up `src/foo.rs` or `src/foo/mod.rs`
- Prefer `src/foo.rs` over `src/foo/mod.rs` (the non-`mod.rs` style) — it avoids multiple files named `mod.rs` which confuse editors
- Keep each module focused on one responsibility — if a module has sub-modules that have sub-modules, the top level is likely too broad

## Visibility

- Default to the minimum visibility: `pub(crate)` > `pub(super)` > `pub`
- Never make a field `pub` on a struct with invariants — use accessor methods
- `pub use` re-exports in `lib.rs` to flatten the public API; do not expose internal module paths to users
- Use `#[non_exhaustive]` on public enums and structs that you may extend in future semver-compatible releases

## `use` declarations

- Import types, not modules, for standard usage: `use std::collections::HashMap` not repeated `std::collections::HashMap::new()`
- Use glob imports (`use foo::*`) only in `#[cfg(test)] mod tests` and prelude modules
- Group imports: `std` → external crates → crate-local (`crate::`, `super::`, `self::`)

## Public API design

- Seal traits that are not meant to be implemented outside the crate using the sealed trait pattern:
  ```rust
  mod private { pub trait Sealed {} }
  pub trait MyTrait: private::Sealed { ... }
  ```
- Use the builder pattern for constructing types with many optional parameters — avoid functions with >3–4 parameters
- Return `impl Trait` from public functions rather than concrete types when the concrete type is an implementation detail
- Add `#[must_use]` to types and functions whose return values must not be silently discarded

## Workspace organisation

- Split a large project into a Cargo workspace with focused crates: `crates/core`, `crates/server`, `crates/cli`
- Keep the `Cargo.toml` dependency list in `[workspace.dependencies]` and inherit with `foo = { workspace = true }` to keep versions consistent
- Each crate should compile and test independently — avoid circular dependencies between workspace crates

## Documentation

- Every `pub` item must have a `///` doc comment
- Start with a one-sentence summary, then a blank line, then details and examples
- Include `# Examples` sections with runnable code for non-trivial APIs — they are tested by `cargo test`
- Use `# Errors` and `# Panics` sections to document failure modes on `pub fn`s that return `Result` or may panic
